\b \cf3 \strokec2 Origin of Dandiya Raas
\b0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl320\sa140\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec5 Originating as devotional \strokec6 Garba\strokec5  dances, which were always performed in Durga's honour, this dance form is actually the staging of a mock-fight between the Goddess and \strokec6 Mahishasura\strokec5 , the mighty demon-king, and is nicknamed "The Sword Dance". During the dance, dancers energetically whirl and move their feet and arms in a complicated, \strokec6 choreographed\strokec5  manner to the tune of the music with various rhythms. The \strokec6 dhol\strokec5  is used as well as complementary percussion instruments such as the \strokec6 dholak\strokec5 , \strokec6 tabla\strokec5 , \strokec6 bongos\strokec5  and others.\
The sticks (
\i dandiya
\i0 s) of the dance represent the \strokec6 swords\strokec5  of Durga. The women wear traditional dresses such as colorful embroidered \strokec6 choli\strokec5 , \strokec6 ghagra\strokec5  and \strokec6 bandhani\strokec5  \strokec6 dupattas\strokec5  (traditional attire) dazzling with mirror work and heavy jewellery. The men wear special turbans and kedias, but this varies regionally.\
Garba is performed before \strokec6 Aarti\strokec5  (worshipping ritual) as devotional performances in the honor of the Goddess, while Dandiya is performed after it, as a part of merriment. Men and women join in for Dandiya Raas, and also for the Garba. The circular movements of Dandiya Raas are much more complex than those of Garba. The origin of these dance performances or \strokec6 Raas\strokec5  is \strokec6 Krishna\strokec5 . Today, Raas is not only an important part of \strokec6 Navratri\strokec5  in Gujarat, but extends itself to other festivals related to harvest and crops as well. The Mers of Saurastra are noted to perform Raas with extreme energy and vigor.\
